'''The Second Map of ''The Lord of the Rings''''' is a map that was drawn by [[J.R.R. Tolkien]] during the writing of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''.<ref name=SecondMap>{{WR|3|XIV}}, p. 433</ref>

It was his working map during the writing of book V of The Lord of the Rings. It has map-squares of 2 centimetres side. Its scale is 2 centimetres for 100 miles. The map squares have the same letters and numbers as on [[The First Map of The Lord of the Rings]]. It was drawn in black ink. Red ink was used for a few alterations. In the final state corrections and additions were made in blue ink, in blue crayon and pencil.<ref name=SecondMap/> J.R.R. Tolkien used contour lines for the mountains and hills on this map.<ref name=ContourLines>{{WR|3|XIV}}, pp. 433-435</ref> Lossarnach seems to have been a larger region than on the [[General Map of Middle-earth]], but it is possible that the long name did not fit in the small space of the real size of the region of Lossarnach.<ref>{{WR|3|XIV}}, p. 436</ref> It includes a dot with the name [[Tarnost]] in the map square Q 12,<ref name=Tarnost>{{WR|3|XIV}}, p. 437</ref> southeast of the crossings over the river [[Ringló]] and on the northeasternmost slopes of the mountains of [[Belfalas]].<ref>{{WR|3|XIV}}, "The Second Map (West)", p. 434</ref> Tarnost is not included on any other map.<ref name=Tarnost/> In addition, the line of the journey of [[Frodo]], [[Sam]] and [[Gollum]] from the [[Emyn Muil]] to the [[Black Gate]] is included on the map.<ref>{{WR|3|XIV}}, Notes, note 1, p. 438</ref>

The Second Map of ''The Lord of the Rings'' has not been published, but redrawings drawn by [[Christopher Tolkien]] of its western and eastern portion with the vertical line of squares with the number 14 repeated on both portions are included in the book ''[[The War of the Ring]]'', in chapter XIV "The Second Map".<ref name=ContourLines/> The contents of the map are described in the same chapter.<ref>{{WR|3|XIV}}, pp. 433, 436-439</ref>

